      <h2 class="section-toggle"><span class="collapse-arrow">&#9654;</span> Overview</h2>
      <div class="collapsible-content" style="display:none">
        <p class="section-desc">
          TAOM includes <strong>300 custom melee weapons</strong> across <strong>13 cultures</strong> (with 3 more planned).
          Each weapon has unique blade weight, damage factors and crafting pieces. <strong
            >Cultural weapon modifiers</strong
          > adjust damage_factor values to complete the balance triangle alongside troop skills and armor protection. This
          analysis computes <strong>estimated damage</strong> using the full TaleWorlds physics simulation.
        </p>
        <p class="section-desc">
          Weapon quality reflects each culture's craftsmanship. Noldor elves forge the finest blades (+10 points above
          average), while crude orc-work from Dol Guldur sits at the bottom (-3 points). Isengard's industrial forges
          serve as the baseline (0 points). Hero/legendary weapons are exempt from cultural modifiers.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="info-section collapsible-section" data-collapsed="true">
      <h2 class="section-toggle">
        <span class="collapse-arrow">&#9654;</span> How Bannerlord Calculates Damage <span class="nerdy-note"
          >(fair warning: this is very math and nerdy)</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="collapsible-content" style="display:none">
        <p class="section-desc">
          Bannerlord doesn't use simple stat tables — it runs a <strong>full physics simulation</strong> for every weapon.
          The damage numbers you see in-game are the result of a multi-step pipeline extracted from decompiled game code (v1.3.12).
          Our calculations match in-game values to within 1-2 points.
        </p>

        <div class="formula-pipeline">
          <div class="pipeline-step">
            <div class="step-number">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>Weapon Assembly</h3>
              <p>
                Each crafted weapon is built from <strong>4 pieces</strong> (blade, guard, handle, pommel). The engine computes
                the weapon's total <strong>weight</strong>, <strong>reach</strong>, <strong>center of mass</strong>, and <strong
                  >moment of inertia</strong
                > using the parallel axis theorem — just like real physics.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-inline">
                <code>I<sub>total</sub> = &Sigma;(I<sub>piece</sub> + m<sub>piece</sub> &times; d&sup2;)</code>
                <span class="formula-label">where d = distance from piece center to weapon center of mass</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="pipeline-step">
            <div class="step-number">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>Swing &amp; Thrust Speed</h3>
              <p>
                Speed is calculated via a <strong>3-layer muscle torque simulation</strong>. Each layer models a muscle
                group (shoulder, arm, wrist) applying torque against the weapon's inertia with drag.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-inline">
                <code>torque = min(power / speed, max_torque) - speed &times; drag</code>
                <span class="formula-label">Iterated at 0.01s timesteps until target angle/distance is reached</span>
              </div>
              <p class="step-note">
                Two-handed weapons get <strong>+40% arm inertia</strong> and <strong>+50% stopping torque</strong> from the
                second hand. Polearms (wide grip) get additional multipliers on top of that. This is why the same blade deals
                different damage in one-handed vs two-handed mode.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="pipeline-step">
            <div class="step-number">3</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>Energy Transfer (Swing)</h3>
              <p>
                Swing damage uses <strong>rotational kinetic energy transfer</strong> at the impact point. The engine computes
                KE before and after the collision:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-inline">
                <code>magnitude = 0.067 &times; (KE<sub>before</sub> - KE<sub>after</sub>)</code>
                <span class="formula-label"
                  >KE = &frac12;mv&sup2; + &frac12;I&omega;&sup2; (translational + rotational)</span
                >
              </div>
              <p class="step-note">
                The game sweeps across <strong>5 impact points</strong> near the blade tip (0.93 to sweet spot) and takes
                the maximum — simulating the optimal hit zone on the blade.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="pipeline-step">
            <div class="step-number">4</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>Energy Transfer (Thrust)</h3>
              <p>Thrust uses <strong>linear kinetic energy</strong> with the arm's weight added to the weapon mass:</p>
              <div class="formula-inline">
                <code>magnitude = 0.125 &times; &frac12; &times; (weight + 2.5) &times; speed&sup2;</code>
                <span class="formula-label">The 2.5 kg represents arm mass behind the thrust</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="pipeline-step">
            <div class="step-number">5</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>Damage Factor</h3>
              <p>
                The physics magnitude is multiplied by the blade's <strong>damage factor</strong> — a float value set per
                crafting piece that represents the blade's cutting/piercing efficiency.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-inline">
                <code>displayed damage = round(magnitude &times; damage_factor)</code>
                <span class="formula-label">This is the number you see in the inventory screen</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="pipeline-step">
            <div class="step-number">6</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>Armor Reduction (Combat)</h3>
              <p>During combat, raw damage is reduced by armor using damage-type-specific formulas:</p>
              <div class="formula-inline">
                <code>reduction = 50 / (50 + armor)</code><br />
                <code>damage = blunt_component + sharp_component</code>
                <span class="formula-label"
                  >Cut: 10% blunt pass-through, 50% armor threshold · Pierce: 25% / 33% · Blunt: 60% / 20%</span
                >
              </div>
              <p class="step-note">
                <strong>Cut</strong> damage is most affected by armor (only 10% passes through as blunt). <strong
                  >Blunt</strong
                > damage ignores armor the most (60% pass-through). <strong>Pierce</strong> is in between.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="formula-summary">
          <h3>Weapon Description Modes</h3>
          <p>
            Some crafting templates produce <strong>multiple weapon modes</strong>. For example, the TwoHandedSword
            template creates 3 descriptions: <em>OneHandedBastardSword</em>, <em>TwoHandedSword</em>, and <em
              >OneHandedBastardSwordAlternative</em
            >. The game checks each description in order — the first one where all blade pieces are registered becomes
            the primary mode shown in the inventory. This is why Anduril (a bastard sword) shows one-handed stats
            despite being on a two-handed template.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <section class="info-section collapsible-section" data-collapsed="true">
    <h2 class="section-toggle"><span class="collapse-arrow">&#9654;</span> Quick Comparison</h2>
    <div class="collapsible-content" style="display:none">
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table class="comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Culture</th>
              <th class="skill-col">Melee</th>
              <th class="skill-col">Ranged</th>
              <th class="skill-col">Avg Melee</th>
              <th class="skill-col">Avg Ranged</th>
              <th class="skill-col">Melee %</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {
              cultures.map((c) => {
                const pctNum = parseInt(c.meleePercent);
                const pctCls = isNaN(pctNum)
                  ? 'mod-zero'
                  : pctNum > 130
                    ? 'mod-warn'
                    : pctNum > 110
                      ? 'mod-pos'
                      : pctNum < 70
                        ? 'mod-crit'
                        : pctNum < 90
                          ? 'mod-neg'
                          : 'mod-zero';
                return (
                  <tr>
                    <td class="culture-cell" style={`background: ${c.color}22; border-left: 3px solid ${c.color}`}>
                      <a href={`#${c.id}`}>{c.name}</a>
                    </td>
                    <td class="center culture-cell" style={`background: ${c.color}15`}>
                      {c.meleeWeapons || '—'}
                    </td>
                    <td class="center culture-cell" style={`background: ${c.color}15`}>
                      {c.rangedWeapons || '—'}
                    </td>
                    <td class="center">{c.avgMelee || '—'}</td>
                    <td class="center">{c.avgRanged || '—'}</td>
                    <td class={`center ${pctCls}`}>{c.meleePercent}</td>
                  </tr>
                );
              })
            }
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="table-legend">
        <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot mod-pos-bg"></span> 110-130% — Above average</span>
        <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot mod-warn-bg"></span> &gt;130% — Potentially overpowered</span>
        <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot mod-neg-bg"></span> 70-90% — Below average</span>
        <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot mod-crit-bg"></span> &lt;70% — Potentially underpowered</span>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="info-section collapsible-section" data-collapsed="true">
    <h2 class="section-toggle"><span class="collapse-arrow">&#9654;</span> Balance Concerns</h2>
    <div class="collapsible-content" style="display:none">
      <div class="concerns-list">
        {
          balanceConcerns.map((concern) => (
            <div class={`concern-item concern-${concern.severity}`}>
              <div class="concern-header">
                <span class={`concern-badge concern-badge-${concern.severity}`}>{concern.severity}</span>
                <strong>{concern.culture}</strong>
              </div>
              <p class="concern-issue">{concern.issue}</p>
              <p class="concern-rec">{concern.recommendation}</p>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="info-section collapsible-section" data-collapsed="true">
    <h2 class="section-toggle"><span class="collapse-arrow">&#9654;</span> Culture Details</h2>
    <div class="collapsible-content" style="display:none">
      {
        cultures.map((c) => (
          <div
            id={c.id}
            class="culture-card"
            style={`background: ${c.color}1a; border: 1px solid ${c.color}40; border-left: 3px solid ${c.color}`}
          >
            <div class="culture-header">
              <h3 style={`color: ${c.color}`}>{c.name}</h3>
              <div class="culture-meta">
                <span class="culture-badge" style={`background: ${c.color}25; color: ${c.color}`}>
                  {c.alignment === 'good'
                    ? 'Free Peoples'
                    : c.alignment === 'neutral'
                      ? 'Neutral Kingdom'
                      : 'Forces of Darkness'}
                </span>
                <span class="culture-badge" style={`background: ${c.color}20; color: ${c.color}cc`}>
                  {c.race}
                </span>
                {c.meleeWeapons + c.rangedWeapons > 0 && (
                  <span class="culture-badge" style={`background: ${c.color}20; color: ${c.color}cc`}>
                    {c.meleeWeapons + c.rangedWeapons} weapons
                  </span>
                )}
                {c.meleePercent !== '—' && (
                  <span class="culture-badge" style={`background: ${c.color}20; color: ${c.color}cc`}>
                    {c.meleePercent} melee
                  </span>
                )}
              </div>
            </div>

            <p class="culture-identity">{c.identity}</p>

            {c.primaryWeapons.length > 0 && (
              <div class="culture-weapons">
                <strong>Primary Weapons:</strong> {c.primaryWeapons.join(' · ')}
              </div>
            )}

            <div class="modifiers-grid">
              {c.strengths.length > 0 && (
                <div class="mod-section strengths">
                  <h4>Strengths</h4>
                  <ul>
                    {c.strengths.map((s) => (
                      <li>
                        <span class="mod-skill">{s.stat}</span>
                        <span class="mod-value pos">{s.mod}</span>
                        <span class="mod-note">{s.note}</span>
                      </li>
                    ))}
                  </ul>
                </div>
              )}

              {c.weaknesses.length > 0 && (
                <div class="mod-section weaknesses">
                  <h4>Weaknesses</h4>
                  <ul>
                    {c.weaknesses.map((w) => (
                      <li>
                        <span class="mod-skill">{w.stat}</span>
                        <span class="mod-value neg">{w.mod}</span>
                        <span class="mod-note">{w.note}</span>
                      </li>
                    ))}
                  </ul>
                </div>
              )}
            </div>

            {c.notes && <p class="culture-notes">{c.notes}</p>}
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="info-section collapsible-section" data-collapsed="true">
    <h2 class="section-toggle"><span class="collapse-arrow">&#9654;</span> Weapon Class Averages</h2>
    <div class="collapsible-content" style="display:none">
      <p class="section-desc">
        Cross-culture average estimated damage per weapon class after cultural modifiers. These represent the global
        baseline for each weapon type.
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table class="baseline-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Weapon Class</th>
              <th>Avg Swing</th>
              <th>Avg Thrust</th>
              <th>Cultures</th>
              <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {
              weaponClassAverages.map((wc) => (
                <tr>
                  <td>{wc.weaponClass}</td>
                  <td>{wc.avgSwing || '—'}</td>
                  <td>{wc.avgThrust || '—'}</td>
                  <td>{wc.cultures}</td>
                  <td class="note-cell">{wc.note}</td>
                </tr>
              ))
            }
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="info-section collapsible-section" data-collapsed="true">
    <h2 class="section-toggle"><span class="collapse-arrow">&#9654;</span> Damage Distribution</h2>
    <div class="collapsible-content" style="display:none">
      <p class="section-desc">
        Expected damage hierarchy based on weapon physics. Two-handed weapons should deal roughly 1.5-2x the damage of
        their one-handed counterparts due to higher blade weight and longer swing arcs.
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table class="baseline-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Weapon Types</th><th>Expected Range</th><th>Current Avg</th><th>Status</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr
              ><td>Tier 1 — Light</td><td>1H Swords, 1H Axes</td><td>50-90</td><td>62-69</td><td class="status-ok"
                >OK</td
              ></tr
            >
            <tr
              ><td>Tier 2 — Medium</td><td>2H Swords, Polearms</td><td>70-110</td><td>52-102</td><td class="status-low"
                >Low (polearms)</td
              ></tr
            >
            <tr
              ><td>Tier 3 — Heavy</td><td>2H Axes, Maces</td><td>90-140</td><td>71-120</td><td class="status-ok">OK</td
              ></tr
            >
            <tr><td>Tier 4 — Crushing</td><td>2H Maces</td><td>100-160</td><td>118</td><td class="status-ok">OK</td></tr
            >
            <tr
              ><td>Thrust-Focused</td><td>Pikes</td><td>40-70</td><td>40/55 swing/thrust</td><td class="status-ok"
                >OK</td
              ></tr
            >
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

